de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sempill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English, Scottish:  see  Semple  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Semple","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): nickname from Middle English, Older Scots, and Old French <i>simple</i> ‘simple, straightforward, humble’ (from Latin <i>simplus</i>). The Scottish name was taken to Ulster in the 17th century, and a Scottish family of this name held the hereditary post of Sheriff of Renfrewshire from the 13th century.","English: variant of   Sample  ."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese: written 井伊 ‘well’ and ‘that’, the name one of Japan's great daimyō families, originally based in Tōtōmi (now part of Shizuoka prefecture), later in Kōzuke (now Gunma prefecture) and Ōmi (now Shiga prefecture). Other variants of the name substitute either character with similar sounding characters such as 飯 ‘cooked rice’, 居 ‘residence’, and so forth. It was formerly Romanized as <b>Iyi</b>. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>II</i> (meaning ‘the second’, i.e. ‘the younger’ of the two bearers of the name) is apparently also counted as a surname <i>Ii</i>.","History: Ii Naomasa (1561–1602) was awarded lands in Kōzuke and Ōmi for his service in the civil wars that won the shōgunate (military dictatorship) for Tokugawa Ieyasu. His family built the beautiful castle of Hikone, which still stands. His descendant Ii Naosuke (1815–1860) ruled Japan for two years as Tairō (Great Elder) and played a major part in signing treaties that opened Japan to foreign trade at the end of the Tokugawa Shōgunate. He was assassinated by adherents of the anti-foreign party."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas de Sempill II of Eliotstoun was born in 1332, in Scotland, his father, Sir William I de Sempill of Eliotstoun, was 42 and his mother, Lady William de Sempill, was 33. He had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with Margaret Montgomery. He died in 1383, in Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1332–1383":"1332–1383","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","1348–1400":"1348–1400","1358–Male":"1358–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1367–Female":"1367–Surnud","1370–1453":"1370–1453","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1383":"1383","1370":"1370","1290":"1290","1348":"1348","1358":"1358","1367":"1367","1400":"1400","1334":"1334","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1365":"1365","1453":"1453","January 1, 1358":"1. jaanuar 1358","Eliotstoun, Renfrewshire, scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Renfrewshire, Strathclyde, Scotland, United K